Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits", which are used to move forward in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time the account holder, examiners, cash issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the trading bitcoins are available in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to insert this new transaction into this book.
This is about a mathematical task that is started on computers, while the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a backup of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number before the whole is "hatched".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is correct.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated from the network and the other will remain unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halfed, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided into a hundred million, which allows a certain amount of space...
In addition, the difficulty of the task with any improvement in computing performance is increased.
