Last week, Poland was admitted to a ministerial meeting of the member countries of the European Space Organisation ESA as the twenty-second member of this space authority. Poland is thus the second member country from the former East bloc (according to the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The way of Poland into space began freely much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos had been busy with space travel, which did not always come to an understanding.
I recall here, for example, the talk by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Enter into the Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years, Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the prize REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, because one of the craters was named after him on the lost side of the moon.
Already in 1925, a railway drive was built in Poland for which a rocket was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rockets should be used to start or to brake the drain.
The information to be provided is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with missiles.
The research was carried out by the Institute of Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents submitted, it is evident that research has been carried out until the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted freely by the entry into force of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, in the press, the design of a photo-electric hunting dragon originated by Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda voietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymcásowy Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish space company (Polishe Towarizvo Astronautique) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, where four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be seen that the exploration of space would have a future.
At its beginning in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the 1951 International Space Federation, and in fact PTA was already a regular member in autumn 1956.
The following year, he became the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Vice-President of the International Federation for Space.
He had been in this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in 1959 began in the Błūdów-Wuiste Flight Tests with the two-stage RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used to monitor high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was introduced.
A successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 missile developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differ in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B above 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C above 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Force Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR Committee for Space Research in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space space research with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became a second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
